{"title":"Home EEG Assessment Confirms Correlation between Alzheimer's and Reduced Deep Sleep","author":"Deep Sleep","date":"2022-09-04","category":"Deep Sleep","heroImage":"https://www.nia.nih.gov/sites/default/files/inline-images/brain_slices_alzheimers_0.jpg","article":"https://alz-journals.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/full/10.1002/trc2.12347","body":"<p>A study of 26 mild to moderate Alzheimer's disease patients has shown through home PSG recordings that AD sufferers spend less time in Deep Sleep compared to healthy control participants.</p><p><br></p><p>Disrupted sleep appears to be common in Alzheimer's patients, resulting in less REM and Deep sleep.&nbsp;The advent of higher-grade consumer EEG headband devices has allowed for testing and monitoring of Alzheimer's patents in their own homes.&nbsp;This recent study confirms other research results which have shown impaired Slow Wave Sleep (Deep Sleep) in this patients.</p><p><br></p>"}